Does your house have far too much empty space for its own good? or is it just missing some large 'thing' in the corner? if you answered yes to either of those, then this tripod lamp should be right up your alley. This massive structure that now dominates my study is most delightful and if you fancy making one too, it's really rather easy. and only needs a handful of non-printed items. So far i have used:
3 off 12x21x2400mm wooden battens (each cut into 3 off 800mm long bits)
3 off M3x15 cap screws
3 off M3x25 cap screws
6 off M3 full nuts & washers
an Ikea pendant bulb holder that came with the lampshade.
a plug
2m of pretty wire
some cord to tie the legs together Printed parts
1 off hub
3 off leg to hub
3 off leg top
3 off leg bottom
6 off leg cams
6 off packers (for the cams to press against so you mess up the wood too much)
(i have kindly included the inventor files and .STEP files of all the bits as .stl files aren't much cop, to me at least) (now, if you don't use an ikea pendant lampshade with a free bulb holder thing that's meant to hang from the roof, I believe that you could use a bulb holder sort of like http://www.amazon.co.uk/Brass-Safety-Switch-Holder-Shade/dp/B007MPBSTI/ref=sr_1_13?ie=UTF8&qid=1446165781&sr=8-13&keywords=bulb+holder
and a length of M10 threaded tube like
http://www.amazon.co.uk/M10-Threaded-Pre-cut-chandelier-projects/dp/B004ZK3X14/ref=sr_1_2?ie=UTF8&qid=1446165957&sr=8-2&keywords=m10+tube
You will then need to reduce the hole in the printed 'hub' part to suit whatever you use.
If you go for a metal option, you will need to use 3 core wire in order to earth the metal holder.) Assembly is pretty self-explanatory so long as you have cut the bits of wood to all the same lengths Please note that i take no responsibility if you're stupid enough to electrocute yourself, it's dodgy stuff this electric malarkey. UPDATE 1
I've added a top hub that takes a brass bulb holder with a 50mm long threaded tube to hold it on. you will have to drill a couple holes in the tube for your wires to the switch to feed through.
oh yeah, the hub also has a void inside to take a pull chain switch coz who doesn't want that!!
as it turns out, everything you need for this version is available in the B&Q wiring department.

It prints well, and fits together well, however if I were to redo it, I may combine some of the parts rather than having separate assemblies (but for experimenting separate assemblies will help since you can just change one part if it needs to be redesigned or changed). I don't have a sensor so I cannot test the functionality myself.

Just use the m3 nuts and bolt that came with the printer to assemble this. 
If you want to use the original E3Dv6 fans that came with the hot-end you can just print the carriage and the mount only. 
The fan-mount is for a 40mm fan so one fan could cool both hot-ends. The 4th piece is for mounting the cooling fan for the prints if you are going to be using PLA. 
You can use the same screws to attach the x-carriage to the ball-bearing linear sliders (may need two more for the last two holes at the bottom). Other than that it is self-explanatory.

title: Cheap/generic webcam mount for Da Vinci or other printers

description.text:
I loved the design from guido666 for a permanent webcam mount, but I always found that my webcams were fidgety, the wire was stiff and the camera would often drift off center of the print bed so I couldn't monitor the prints. This works for both the davinci 1 and 2. It may work with the 1.0A and others with some modifications, someone try and let me know! I took the original idea, hooking the bracket onto the Da Vinci frame and made a few modifications. I made the webcam bolt directly onto the bracket and made the camera stop drifting. First you can print the parts. The main bracket is the biggest part. The post comes in a few different sizes based on how high you want the camera and how long your bolts are. Find an M3 bolt at least an inch/25mm long. Print a post that is 10mm shorter than the bolt you have (the bracket is ~5mm thick and you want to screw 5mm into the webcam). Now to mod the webcam. I use the same webcam mentioned in the original post because it is RIDICULOUSLY cheap and I find it works great. There are a lot of sources on amazon, (mentioned at the bottom) but as long as you use one that looks like this, it should work. They all have mediocre reviews, but one thing I've noticed is that if the webcam has an audio plug as well as the USB, it seems to be higher quality. Unscrew the top part from the base as shown (picture 2) we will not use the base at all. You can slice off the extra part with a razor (picture 3, don't mess it up too much because we're going to thread it. Now drill it with a 2.5mm drill bit (picture 4, approximately 3/32"). Now take an M3x0.5mm pitch tap (I'd suggest getting one, they're very useful for all printing projects because they're really common hardware, great for assembling small gadgets) and make an m3 thread in that same hole all the way through (picture 5, rotate the cradle part to go through). You can probably force/form a thread with an m3 bolt and it might even fit tighter, but a tap definitely works. You'll use this to attach it. Now take the top part and unscrew one of the two screws(picture 7b). It's possible yours is made differently (the cradle part may have screws into the round part, so unscrew these instead). Now pull out one arm of the cradle (picture 7) and place an oring (rubber band will do) on the part so that when you screw it back in the oring will make it tougher to rotate and it will hold it's position better (picture 7c). Repeat for the other side. Now assemble as shown in picture 8 (I'm using a different "bracket" part, but you get the idea. Put a 25-25mm m3 bolt through the bottom of the bracket (put a washer between the bolt head and the bracket if you can), another oring or rubber band around the bolt sitting on top of the bracket (if you have one), then slide the hollow post (picture 6, 6b) onto the bolt (you will have to poke through the solid layer that's there to make it more printable), then screw it into the camera. Make sure the bolt doesn't screw up into the camera, although it may not matter if the angle is right. Now place the bracket in the holes of the Da Vinci frame and you're good to go. You want a 006 size oring (1/8" ID, 1/4" OD ~3.18mm ID, 6.35mm OD) and can find many on amazon.
I used (http://www.amazon.com/006-Buna-N-O-Ring-Durometer-Black/dp/B000FN0V06/ref=sr_1_1?ie=UTF8&qid=1446177335&sr=8-1&keywords=006+oring) also good or many projects with M3 hardware. Many webcams can be found on amazon, but I used (http://www.amazon.com/30-0M-Webcam-Camera-Desktop-Laptop/dp/B0090CS29A/ref=cm_cr_pr_product_top?ie=UTF8) A prime option can be found here (http://www.amazon.com/Fosmon-Megapixel-Microphone-Meeting-Support/dp/B008ROOOB2/ref=cm_cr_pr_product_top?ie=UTF8)

title: precision paste extruder based on screw frosting device
license: Creative Commons - Attribution - Non-Commercial - No Derivatives

description.text:
This is an amazing paste extruder based on one I've been working with with a HYREL 3D printer. It uses a geared down stepper motor and a paste (frosting/clay) extruder you can find many places. There is a patent on the frosting extruder part, actuated by a screw/plunger (USPTO# 7413429 B1, 7416400 B1, and 7476097 B1) but as far as I know this just means you can make/sell this part. There are many sources that I've seen (amazon, walmart.com) for this part of the extruder, but as far as I know, the official source can be found here (makinsclay.com). The idea is the stepper motor rotates its axle, but the body is rotationally constrained by a linear rail. The rail allows it to move up and down with minimal friction as the rotation of the screw slowly actuates the plunger. The printed parts are the motor bracket (that can be adjusted for various stepper, and I'll likely swap it for a 50:1 planetary geared NEMA11or NEMA 14 in the future. The other printed part is the syringe holder and part that bolts to the x carriage (intended for a prusa i3 with 20 mm wide holes for m3 bolts). Let me know and I can make alternate sizes/mountings. The other necessary parts are a 19.19:1 geared stepper from stepperonline.com (calibration of steps/mm is 2001619.19/1.411111111 (threads per inch for 5/16-18 screw thread) = 43517.48. This is with a 17mm ID "syringe" (of sorts). You may find it beneficial to make the calibration 435.1748 and use a filament diameter of 1.7. Since the volume is proportional to the radius^2, reducing the radius by 10 and extruder calibration by 10^2 will cancel out. This will make speeds more comparable to traditional 1.75mm filament. And a linear rail. More info later. These are expensive, but necessary. That's the nitty gritty, I'll be posting revisions as I get them, and I have a UV curing add-on and heater setup that you can find details on here: http://onlinelibrary.wiley.com/doi/10.1002/marc.201600236/abstract. I'm making a guide to building a bioprinter, so I'll have better documentation once I get that together. https://www.amazon.com/dp/B00PNEQKOS

The LED of DJI S800 ESCs is soldered in the bottom of the PCB and protrudes. This makes very easy to damage the LED if you not take care when leaving the arm in the ground. Also, l wanted to label the arms to know instantly which motor I'm installing in the frame... Solution: Make labelled LED domes. Taking as base the Adafruit's LED Dome, I've modded it removing the little wings and adding a label with the motor number. The dome not only protects the LED but also doubles as a tulip making easy to see the light especially from sides. If you think it deserves downloading... Please leave a Like!

Allow one nozzle to print with 2 colors. This is still a work in progress, but for the moment, the print can be attached to E3D V5 (at least) and allow to insert 2 filament drive by 2 steppers. The ideea is to connect the hotend thermisotrs to the RAMPS for head 1 and head 2 to mimic 2 hotends with correct temperatures. When the color is changed the actual color will need to be retracted 60mm (for the actual build), and the second color will be inserted with 65mm. The reason i made this method is because is hard to calibrate 2 extruders on a perfect height, and also this mode will prevent the unused extruder to leak. Hope this weekend to post more informations / video Printer settings:
-Because i already prepared the thermistor and the heater for the second nozzle i put them together with kapton tape. Cura and Slic3r settings:
-Set the extruders offset to 0
-Set the temperature for the second nozzle to 22 (or the value in your room) ( Once the 1st nozzle and the bed get the correct temperature, if there is a difference between 2nd nozzle and the temp you set, manually increase / decrease the temp to match the environment temp
  • On Cura, go to "Start/End - GCode and comment the line G1 F200 E-{retraction_dual_amount} from start2.gcode
  • Set the retraction amount on both extruders to 160mm (for the filament to stop on the PTFE tube)
    • On the printer, insert the first filament until it is extruder, and for the second filament insert it until it is closed to the pneumatic nut. PS: On Marlin firmware, the mintemp warning will need to be set to your room temp - 3 degree Warning: Keep the printer under surveillance. If something is happening with the thermistor, the printer will not stop the heater and in contrary, will try to compensate the temperature.

title: TinyBoy Pi hangers - updated to include B+, pi2 and pi3

description.text:
This is just a simple pair of brackets I've made to hold a raspberry pi onto the side of the TinyBoy printer (Mini-fabricator).
Countersunk on the printer side for countersink M2.5 bolts.
Best printed lying on the side as in the picture to prevent weakness at the top corners. Updated (01-Nov-2015) to include a 7mm hole for an "off" switch and a 3mm hole for a power LED. Updated (14-Apr-2016) to include hangers for Pi B+, Pi2 and Pi3. Files required as follows:
Pi rev 2 without switch and LED: Pi_Hanger_A.stl & Pi_Hanger_B.stl
Pi rev 2 with switch and LED: Po_Hanger_A.stl and Pi_Hanger_b_with_LED__switch.stl
Pi B+, Pi2 or Pi3 without switch and LED: Pi Hanger_b+_a.stl x 2 (apologies, not manifold but prints fine anyway - I blame Sketchup)
Pi B+, Pi2 or Pi3 with switch and LED: Pi Hanger_b+_a.stl & Pi Hanger_b+_b.stl Schematic is included for the switch and LED. I'll try to get the script uploaded when I get a chance to get it working on Jessie. Updated (05-May-2016)
Simplified schematic and python script uploaded. I highly recommend using the switch on Pin 5 (GPIO 3) as this also allows you to wake the pi up after a shutdown by pressing the button again.
Running scripts at startup has changed somewhat in Jessie. We now need to use systemd to schedule them. I followed the guide here which allowed it to run correctly:
http://www.raspberrypi-spy.co.uk/2015/10/how-to-autorun-a-python-script-on-boot-using-systemd/
